  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Origins trace back to laws combating organized crime in the 1930s\n- Initial focus was on preventing criminal enterprises from disguising illegal proceeds\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - United States\n- First comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n3. International Development\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global problem\n- Increased focus on drug trafficking proceeds\n\n4. FATF Establishment (1989)\n- Financial Action Task Force created\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Issued recommendations for national legal and regulatory systems\n\n5. Major Legislative Milestones\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotics (1988)\n- Emerald Isle Initiative (1990s) targeting international financial crime\n\n6. Post-9/11 Developments\n- Patriot Act (2001) significantly expanded AML regulations\n- Greater emphasis on terrorist financing prevention\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n\n7. Ongoing Global Enforcement\n- Continual refinement of legal frameworks\n- Increasing technological sophistication in detection methods",
